            <div type="glosses" subtype="textual">
                <note xml:id="STORMCROSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">Line 4&#x2014;</hi>The meaning and origin of the cross above &#x201C;pigs&#x201D; in line 4 are unknown. Evidently, the mark is a comment on the poem by somebody, 
                    rather than a part of the poem itself. See <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="editorial_rationale_note.php#METAMARKS">Editorial and Encoding Rationale and Methodology: Metamarks</ref>.</p></note>
                
                <note xml:id="BAD" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;Bad&#x201D; (<title type="poem" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>)&#x2014;</hi>Although on the same line as the runover of line 10, 
                    the word clearly is not meant to form part of that runover, as in that case it would intervene between the two syllables of the word, 
                    <hi rend="italic">lightnings</hi>, which is divided by the runover. Rather, the term, which appears in <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s hand, 
                    functions as a metamark&#x2014;not as part of the poem, but as a comment on it.</p></note>
            </div>
